{"/service/ndnp/uuml/batch_uuml_fifteen_ver01/data/sn85058398/paper/1910080901/0313.xml":{"full_text":"ri I\nta 4 THE DAILY STANDARD OGDEN UTAH TUESDAY AUGUST 9 1910 f\nID1rr1Euttttug tttrthttrt\nPublished Daily Except Sundays by Wm Glasmann\n1\nI I\nTHE BUSINESS OUTLOOK\nI j I\nIi A formidable array of unpleasant facts is the summary in\nthe weekly market letter by Henry Clews The New York banker\nplaces much stress on the condition of the corn crop saying that if\nf corn improves so that at harvest time there is a good yield the coun\nt try may be saved from a depression\nI H Should we raiso a 3000000000bushcl crop worth about 2\nr 000000000 to the farmers is Mr Clews statement this will do\nmuch toward checking any serious business reaction On the other\nf I hand oven partial failure of the corn crop might invite serious con\nsequences Another four to six weeks must elapse before corn is\nfully mode Fortunately the latest reports are very favorable for a\ni big yield Wheat too leas been showing marked recuperative pow\ni ers from previous damage All things considered the crop outlook\nis mixed and might be better but still contains some features of pos\nI\nj itivo encouragement\nII Another element of uncertainty is the political situation Re\nI cent events at the West emphasize political discontent and indicate\nI Democratic gains in the election next November Advices from\n1 I Washington also suggest the probability of considerable agitation in\ns I II the early future The business outlook is not altogether satisfactory\nit is now generally recognized that the country has already entered\n1 a period of reaction retrenchment and readjustment Nothing se\nl i vere in this direction is expected but it is generally recognized that\n1I the pace has been too fast and that a period of slowingdown is im\ni i I perative Conditions in the iron trade which is usually considered\nour best trade barometer confirm these views Production of pig\nf iron is running at the rate of about 26000000 annually which is\ni 20 per cent below maximum of the year Prices of iron products\nshow a declining tendency The copper situation continues perplex\ning supplies are increasing to an embarrassing extent and there\nI seems to be no way of restraining the output except by reducing\nI prices to a level that will force shutdown of the weaker concerns\ni The textile trades are experiencing a slight improvement but are\nt embarrassed by the high cost of raw material and many mills\nI arc idle Business failures arc increasing i the total number re\nI I ported in July being 1147 against 1105 a year ago More than 1\n000000000 in new securities were issued in the last six months In\ni July the issues were only about 62000000 compared with 121 i\n1 000000 a year ago Railroad earnings continue to show a liberal\nIncrease in gross but a number of the roads are showing startling\nlosses in net since the increase in wages which went into effect on\nJune 1 Plainly railroads must secure better rates of freight unless\n1 i they are to cut wages and expenses to a point that would be hazard\nI ous Doubtless many of the roads will inaugurate a policy of rigid\neconomy before very long something that will neither be relished\nby labor nor by concerns supplying the railroads with materials and\nequipment\nAccording to Clews the greatest apprehension is not as to crops\ni but as to what the railroads will do The most important factor in\nour business affairs Is the policy of the railroads If the big roads\nI\nI concertedly aim at retrenchment in order to punish the American\nI people for adverse legislation or restrain the Interstate Commerce\ncommission from reducing rates they can make this country a dreary\nplace The railroads are so powerful that they must be held in re\nstraint by the government and if that is impossible they must be\n1 moo government property\nMORE CITY EXPENSES\nNo matter which way we turn increased Salaries and more as\nsistants are asked for For the first time in the history of Ogden\nthe city auditor has asked for a 5 per day assistant and she is\nmodest enough to say that she wantsNan assistant to check up the I\nwaterworks department the city recorders office and the city\ntreasurers office When we consider the very competent persons\nI\nengaged in the auditors office we wonder why none of the depart\ni ments has been checked up Only a few years ago Mrs Harriet Em\nr tnerson was city auditor and did all the work without assistance I\nwhatever Following her was Mrs Hattie Brown and for several\nj years she had no assistance whatever but during the last year of her\nterm in office the city allowed her to appoint an assistant at 40\n1er month who worked one hour or two hours in the evening after I\nUpper The present auditor succeeded Mrs Hattie Brown and she I\nlas received an assistant who gets 100 per month who alone should\n1e able to perform all the duties of the city auditor But here we I\nind the auditor asking for an assistant at the rate of 5 per day\nThe Mayor has promptly vetoed the measure and in his veto has i\nmggested that if an assistant is really necessary the Mayor would t\nlike the honor of appointing that assistant in order to discover why i\nI he present auditors force cannot perform the full duties of the of\nice To this the auditor seriously objects claiming that she alone\nIs responsible for her assistants The council has allowed the 5 per\nlay and the end is not yet\nThere are three able persons in charge of the recorders office\nwith an assistant for the license department There are two persons\nIn the treasurers office and there are two persons in the auditors\noffice Now is added the 5 per day assistant There are practically\nnine persons engaged to keep the records and books of Ogden City\nWe do not believe that any mercantile establishment with the same\nwork to perform would have over four or five persons doing the I\nwork\nIt is remarkable however that the former auditor could get\nalong with one or two hours work in the evening with an assistant\nat 40 per month and now the present auditor has an assistant at\nUOO per month and cannot keep up with the work I\nThere is something wrong and the city council has made a ser\nious mistake in giving the auditor a 5 per day assistant It is an\nentering wedge for future appeals in the same line\nThe little auditing and bookkeeping to be performed by the\ncity auditor and the checking up of the accounts of the various de\nar ments is an easy and pleasant duty and there is no reason why\nfro competent persons could not do that and have time to spare\nI I We repeat that the city council is too liberal in turning down\nI\nthe Mayors veto in reference to salaries and the granting of assist 1\n1 ants to officers elected to perform their duties\nThe city auditor is an estimable young lady but that fact\nshould not outweigh the fact that Ogden is in need of economy and\nthe city administration cannot afford to grant all that is asked for\nby tho different departments There must be a check on these de\nmands and as strict an accounting must be exacted as though the\ncouncilmen and mayor were transacting their own private business\nA little extravagance or undue liberality too often leads to a disre\ngard of all promptings of economy\nThe money being poured out from the city treasury is the wealth\nI of the property owners often drawn from the taxpayers when they\nare not really able to make the sacrifice That thought should be\nI constantly before those trusted with the city expend tureS4\nTO AMUSE AND EDUCATE\nWhen the FourState Fair opens on September 23 the people in\nattendance will be treated to the most pleasing amusement ever pre\nsented at a fair in the West The manager of the exhibition is plan I\nning to accomplish something out of the ordinary by presenting at\ntractions which will excel any similar entertainment in all this reg\nion The idea is to make the Ogden annual exposition the most\ntalked of fair in the intermountain country Gradually that aim is\nbeing attained though not without much patient labor and personal\nsacrifice on the part of those who are entrusted with the success of\nthe undertaking\nThis year an aeroplane ia to make flights over the Fair Grounds\nand it is possible that during the week of amusement an effort will\nbe made by the aviator to reach the top of one of the mighty cliffs\nto the east of Ogden I\ni The Great McHale aerial artist has been engaged to per I\nform each day\nI The Mazeroff troupe of Russians singers instrumentalists and\ndancers are the highest priced attraction engaged by any fair and\ncould not have been obtained were Pantages vaudeville circuit ready\nI to accept their services These foreigners will go from hero to the\nIj Seattle fair and then play in vaudeville on the Pacific Coast\nBelle Stone enclosing herself in a steel globe 20 inches in diam\nI eter will ascend a spiral to a vertical height of 25 feet Her act has i\nnot been duplicated except in one of the large circuses\nI Don Carlos dogs and monkeys will afford endless pleasure for\nthe children\nI There will be a Midwaya tented city of fun and frolic\nWehave presented tho different attractions in detail to give our\nI readers some idea of the scope of the work of the fair people in one\ndirection that of free amusements And yet these entertainments\nare but incidental to the exhibition proper which has to do with the\n1 displaying of the products of four states the gathering and display\ning of which involve almost endless labor\nJUST FOR FUN\nSounded Best When SHoot\nIn a railroad office In West Phila\ndelphia there is an old and trusted\nclerk of Celtic extraction who keeps\nhis associates In n constant state of\ngood humor by an unending Series of\nwitticisms interspersed occasionally\nwith bulls so glaring that oven ho\nhimself has to join In the laugh that\ninvariably follows such a break on\nhis part\nThere was some trouble on tho tel\nephone one day recently and Mike\nas he Is called among his friends lost\nmuch of his usual good nature In his\nefforts to get the gist of a message\nthat was being sent from another of\nfice The man on the other ond of\ntho wire finally became exasperated\nand asked Mike if he was losing his\nhearing\nI can hear you all right until you\nbegin to talk said Mike and then\nI cant understand a word you says\nPhiladelphia Times\nA Big Contract\nWinston Churchill the novelist de\nscribed at a dinner In New York the\ndifference between romanticism and\nrealism in fiction\nTo make my meaning clearer ho I\nended I will take the case of a\nyoung man and girl sweethearts\nThe young man a romanticist said\npassionately to the girl\nDarling it shall be my Hfos ono\npurpose to surround you with every\ncomfort and to anticipate and grant\nyour every wish\nTho girl a realist smiled faintly\nas she answered\nOh Jack how good of you And\nall on 9 a week too Success\nMagazine\nOnce Is Enough\nThe Sunday school lesson was from\nthat Scripture which teaches that If\nyour brother strikes you on the cheep\nyou should turn the other also and en\ndure even for seventy times seven\nJohnny had listened to his teacher\nvery attentively whIle she emphasiz\ned this fact and after the lesson tile\nsuperintendent rose to make a few\nremarks\nNow boys she said how many\ntimes ought another boy to strike you\nbefore you hit him back\nJust about once promptly an\nswered Johnny\nToo Deep For Tears\nTho milkmans horse had run away\nand the contents of tho wagon had\nbeen distributed Impartially over a\nterritory two blocks long and one\nstreet wide\nNo said the driver as he survey\ned tho wreck Im not going to do\nany crying over spilt milk but\nThereupon ho sat down on the edge\nof the sidewalk and his subsequent\nprofanity according to the testimony\nof everybody within hearing esKb\nHshcd v now record Chicago Tri\nbune\nILLNESS\nYou say you were away from the\noffice yesterday because of Illness 1\nsaid the stern employer\nYes replied the young man who\nV\nknow he was discovered Several of\nthe umpires decisions made mo sick\nWashington Star\nHuman Vanity\nSomo women are terribly vain\nsaid the censorious person\nYes replied Mls Cayenne they\nare And by the way eld you over\nnotice a man who was fixing himself\nup to have his photograph taken 1\nWashington Star\nSome Help\nOur help she keeps a watchful eye\nUpon the pantry shelf\nAnd every time she passes by\nOur help sho helps herself\nHarpers Weekly\nCIVIL WAR FRIfiATE\nON tiER LAST TRIP\nNew York Aug STho frigate\nPortmouth one of tho last old squaro\nrigged participants In tho Civil War\nstill afloat weighed anchor today on\nthe first leg of her last journey She\nwill shortly Ball for Seattle where\nshe Is to be transformed into a naval\nmuseum\nThe Portsmouth was built at Ports\nmouth N H1JtJt sue was largely\nmanned by the state of Washington\nand tho claim of their descendants\nwas given first call by the federal\ngovernment although San Francisco\nalso put In a bid for her because she\ntook possession of California in the\nname of the United States Her jour\nney today was brief\nUntil last rear tho Portsmouth was\nkept in commission as a training ship\nfor the New Jersey naval reserves\nRETAILERS GET THE\nWORST OF THE DEAL\nWeekly Sottkment Order of Whole\nsalers Works Great Hard\nship on Grocers\nTho Salt Lake Tribune says\nIt Was anything but a pleasure trip\nthat sixtythree Salt Lake retail gro\ncers took to Ogden canyon Sunday\nThe purpose ot the trip was to dis\ncuss earnestly calmly and with aa\nlittle disturbance as possible the re\ncent edict of the wholesalers of the\ncity requiring tho retail dealer to pay\nfor merchandise purchased from the\nwholesalers at the end of each week\ninstead of monthly as has been done\nin tho pasL The new order will RO\nInto effect on August 15 and the re\ntail dealer who fails to settle up every\nweek will be refused any credit what\never by the wholesale houses of the\ncity and In that event may have to\nclose up business\nThe party of retail grocers won to\nOgdon and then proceeded by special\ncar to the Hermitage whero tho day\nwas spent In serious deliberation The\nmatter of establishing their own com\nmission house was discussed at\nlength and it was found that It would\nrequire at least 500 from each of the\ndealers present to establish such a\nhouse and that was more than many\nOi the small dealers could ralso and\nleave them enough lo carry on liteir\nbusiness So that plan liif practical\nly abandoned\nRetailers Are BUter\nTho members of tho party expressed I\nthemselves freely In regard to the now I\norder issued by the wholesalers and\nmany of them expressed tho belief I\nthat a number of the smaller dealers\nwould be forced out of business\nWhen at least 90 per cent of the\nwasfrcarnero of the city arc paid only\nonce a month and after waiting thir\nty days have to wait ten days longer\nbefore they can draw their checks\ntho grocers believe It is unfair to nsk\nsuch customers to pay their hills 1\nweekly or expect them to do so\nIt was finally decided to endure the I\ninjustice for the present at least and I\nto pay tho bills weekly However a\ncall Is being Issued for a meeting of\nall the retail grocers of the state to I\nbo held November 5 at which the\nmatter will 1 e discussed on a broad\nscale and some plan of action deeded\nupon\nIt has been suggested that a central\nexchange be formed of which every\nretail grocer of the state should he a\nmember and some plan devised\nWhereby they sould order by carloads\ndirect from the manufacturer and\nthen distribute the proflMfi fro nr\nexchango to tho various retailers\nThis It is urged would do away with\ntho middlemens commission At any\nrate the retailers will do a lots of\nscheming between now and November\n5 In order to fix up some plan to oven\nup with the wholesalers\nUTMI BOYS IN\nA BERUN JAil\nA vivid description of tho personal\nexperiences of one of the elders who\nwas among those on whom the Prus\nsian police descended while holding a\nmeeting in Berlin on July 21 which\nwas covered by the Associated Press\ndispatches Is contained In a letter\nfrom Elder Rndger ClaWson son of\nMr and Mrs Spencer Clawaon to\nhis mother dated Berlin July 22 pub\nlished in the Doseret News Tho\nmeeting was broken up by tho police\nand the missionaries were placed In\njail for the nIght but released next\nday with orders to leave the city and\nnot return under penalty of fine and\nImprisonment Following Is an ex\ntract from Elder Clawstms letter\nMy Dear Mother Just a line to\nsay that I reached Berlin yesterday\nafternoon and will leave for Rotter\ndam In the morning giving me just a\nday and a half in one of the finest and\nmost attractive cities In Europe And\nclacka day Im afraid I shall not see\nBerlin again for a long time to como\nThis Is how It happened We wero\nholding meeting hero in a nice hall\nwith a largo attendance of Saints\nand strangers The services wero\nopened with a spirited song and pray\ner A short address was given by\none of too elders in Gorman follow\ned by a quartet of male voices At\nthis point I was introduced and pro\nceeded to speak in English Elder\nClayton ewi of Nephl Clayton pres\nident of the branch translating me\nMy text was the principle of sacri\nfice I gave several Illustrations show\ning that sacrifice brings forth the\nblessings of heaven Referring to the\nSavior I remarked that he brought\nto tho world a message of love of\npeace ofJoy salvation and iq re\nturn was met by a spirit of l\nand persecution\nEnter the Police\nJust as I reached this point tho\npollco entered the room and Inter\nrupted tho meeting They talked rap\nIdly and excitedly I didnt know just\nwhat they wore saying but T seemed\nto know what was going on They\nordered all the women to leave the\nroom and tho men to remain Of tho\nmen present tho missionaries some\n21 In number including President\nThomas McKay and myself wero ar\nrested and taken to police headquar\nters and locked up for the night\nSo you lice my first night in Ber\nlin was spent In Jail The ono redeem\ning feature of this experience was a\nclean bed otherwise It was extreme\nly unpleasant but then you know IJit\nQuito used to that sort of thing but\nto those brethren who had never had\na similar experience It came as a\nheavy Jolt\nThe following day after about IS\nhours confinement we were released\nand banished from Prussia being giv\ni en three days to get out Wo can\nvisit other parts of the German em i\ni plrc but Berlin never unless the ban j\nIshment order is rescinded If wo I\nreturn to this city a pleasant reception i\nawaits lIsHnl and imprisonment I 1\nam leaving today for Rotterdam I\nWe went to jnll without supper\nand came away without breakfast or\ndinner The prison breakfast I pass I\ned up When they handed me a\npiece of coarse strong bread and a i\ncup of coffee much resembling dish\nwater I accepted It of course with a\nI smile but upon closer Investigation I\nwas not so hungry as I thought r was\nThe fare was so repugnant that I al\nready had a feeling of fulness and\nwaited until I got out of prison be\nfore eating\nA JSWERtD NfGROS\nDECOY ADRTISEMET\nI\nST LOUIS Aug 8Miss Lulu\nFchlhammer reported to the noic1\ntoday that she was attacked at a\npistol point last Tuesday night by\nJames B Bradfiold alias Bradford a\nrcgro when she wont to answer I\nwhat proved lo bo a fake o lver j\ntlsement for an ofllco girl Bradfiold\nTOMORROW f\np1 1TjThTiY c r\nI\nr\nU\nAI1A b w\nrmrm\nJ TtfR MPOQ\nL7 a OTS va sic\n0 1 ELEPHANTS\n0\nT1fLS M 0 r 1\nHORSE 14S\n1jyS H S3 t\nASH OW s 41 ASC ro DER1 Sf\nTHAT pQIc1 ITHELOME DECEHDSj rS tllCT PWY AVO I\no 0 1 THE Bl G l AMTOA OAVCC W TWC\nAL OTHERS NOTVNC\nTENT a BURST j j THD\n0 HDMJST\nU SIDE fs n OF OlDCRHA\nAND 2pid ACTINO\nROIL\nITSTIELD r eY secH\nIts Triumphs Reach Beyond the Seas\nY CAPITAL IWVESTED3500OOI\n12SO PERSONS 7OO HORSES I\nJOO CAGES and DENS of WILD ANIMALO 40 ELEPHANTS\npc ooyouc UCNOTH inn AOTO rcATU ca AND\nUV RAILROAD OARO lUU CUROPCAN QCNOATIONol\ny iCHARLEY IJhe Manlike Bicycle BldingChlmpanzBB f u\np THE GREATEST TRAINED ANIMALS EVER 0 CHa\nm\n1 GCC THC PONICO QM THC RCVOLVINQ TAOUCQ a t\nCO AERIALISTS ACID THE 3ICQRI8T6IL DOH8 I\n0 60 ACROBATS AND THE PATTY FRAHK6 y\n00 RDERS THE CRCATCST In the WORLD t\ns L DO CLOVN3 THH WORLDS FUNNY MBH q\nA AXIIV Of CieirMC HKLUOIKO BJliT OUHBIIVO I\nCy lTJucaicAi eoiiMirciurc icao wox 5\n1 DtktrIW ocARCAO Tnt w I roDwut\nt0 THC OMC Or TMC LAICMT 36r Il I\nTCIfT QYCI NADL 7\nI m I I\nis f1 a Q I\nI I\ntl t II\nTHE THRILLER POSITIVELY MOST\nTREMENDOUS OORCCOUS V\nSUPREME\nFREE STREET PARADE\nDESPERADOS\ntin SEEN suet urn eta LRNllo or 7IMC j\nr r tnii K4irjj ir 10 otucs\nreamaic i\nDEATH OCrVIHO One 50 Cent Ticket\nLCAP\nADMITS TO ALL\nA NCRVC Ci1IrDArp OHDER 12 TEARS HAL PRICE\nTWISTINO pGRroRMANoea fflHCAT2andDPM I\nFEAT P0009 OPCH AT I end r P M\nI\nr\ny\nAdmission tickets and reserved seats will be on sale circus\nI day at the UTAHNA DRUG CO at exactly the same prices 1\ncharged at the regular circus ticket wagons\nwas arrested Saturday night whIlo I\nmenacing Miss Bossie Unger after I\ndecoying her by meant of an advar\ntisomont Into a building of which ho\nwas Janitor I\nBradilold according to Miss Fohl\nhammer held a pistol to her head\nwhen she recovered from a faint and\nmade her sign a statement that who I\nvisited the office building on her own\nfieo will I\nThe statement was In Bradflolda\npockets and attached to It was a I\nlock of Miss Fehlhammers hair\nOUTSIDE BUYING NOTED\nON EASTERN MARKETS\nJames A Pollock Co bankers\nand brokers furnish the following\nreceive over their private wire yes\nterday afternoon\nPaine Webber Co letter IJostoiu\nThe Boston market continued very\nwrong throughout most of tljjj day\nwith outside buying coming in very\nfreely Sharp advances were mode\nthroughout the list We still think\nI that tho coppers can bo bought as\nthe metal situation Is fast getting in\nto a strong position Tho Copper Pro\nducers report was made at noon\nshowing an Increase of 2 11 million\nrounds The foreign visible supply I\nas supposed to have decreased about\n11000000 pounds This should be\nconstrued as a bullish factor Tho\ngovernment crop report was Jlsap\nI pointing but think it has been dis\ncounted as since tIll first of August\nrains have fallen In the much need\ncd slates helping out tho crop ma\nterially On the announcement of\nI tlis report stocks broke sharply In\nNew York but rallied toward the\nclose On any of those dips would\nLuke on a few taking advantage of\nrallies to sell out\nLogan Bryan stock letter New\nYork The market advanced steadily\nuntil the government crop llguros\nwere published after which time it\nbecame decidedly feverish The strout\nwaR rather inclined to look for a\nhigher condition on corn but the fact\nthat the heavy selling in tho last\nhour was well absorbed and the re\ncovery so rapid the feeling at tho\nclose rather inclined towards optim\nism especially as weather reports I\nof late from the southwest have boon\nmore satisfactory than heretofore\nThere appeared to be moderate dia\ntibutlon on the advance but tIll\npressure was not of an aggressive\ncharacter but at the same time tho I\nshort interest displayed considerable\nnervousness It should ho remember I\ned that we are passing through it\ncritical period with regard to the\ncorn crop on which great hopos bare\nbeen based and therefore tempor\nary strength In tho security markets\nshould not bo permitted to mislead\none Tho monthly report of tho Steel\nCorporation to bo issued on the 10th\nV7ltli regard to unfilled tonnage will\nprobably be awaIted with interest\nHornblowor letter Boston Stocks\nshowed more strength and activity\nthan has been seen for ti long Hmo\nI Traders worked on the long side and\nfor the first time In months thora\nas a good bit of outside buying\nhere arc few alooka for sale and\nalthdligh we hare had considerable\nof a rally from the low prices of tho\nyear the best judges Rtlll think that\nthe long side is the right one for tho\nlong pull but advise caution on buy\ning after extreme advances prefer\nnng to await weak days which are\nbound to come Tho changes for the\nday ranged from a point to three\npoints in the general list and al\nthough New York weakened some\nwhat in tho late afternoon tho ad\nvances were well maintained The\nclosing was steady with a fair do\nnmnd\nCONDUCTORS ARE\nTO TALK RATES\nChicago Aug Passengers trav\neling over many of the leading rail\nroad systems soon may be enter\ntained en route by dissertations from\nthe conductors and othor train em\nployes on the advantages to be le\nlived from allowing the roads to ad\nunco freight rates It tho advice ur\nI prominent railway executives to their\nemployes is followed\ni Jt was learned today that a pamph\nlet Is circulating among the forty\nthousand employes of the lllinotff I\nCentral appealing to tho employes to\nstudy the railroad question and dil\ncuss it among themselves until they\nrut thoroughly conversant with tin\nactual conditions from the financial\nttiv point Having done this oacl\nonploye is urged to try to convert\nduring the course of a year three or\nInur men who are now opposed to\nthe railroads\nCARD OF THANKS 1\n3\nWo arc truly appreciative of the t\nmany acts of kindness extended us a I\nduring our recent great bereavement\nIn the loss of our son Bernard J er\nney by neighbors and friends Espec I\nially are we grateful to those who\ncomforted us at the funeral services\nby words and songs and also for the t\nbountiful offerings of flowers and\nsincerely trust tho Divino Maker nuts 1\nrawarl you all 0\nMR and MIls M J KERNEY l\nli\nREAD THE CLASS ADS TODAY\nI\ntUIn op U\nL r\nrp f I1 Jo x\nul 11 J tf I T m 1\nN it 11 1I T f 11\n195 rJrDEJyrh J T rJPULAR 195\nSit 0 E SAL E II e V svozsroz\nII I J iJJBJV SnflE HOE SALE\nThe seasons eleao sap sale osi A m m D y D lf fl A The 400Q m ades sire flay small\njf O T3 TIT M D A Y\nOmords RJIIl all flea\naUBeaftbers ize am J LL t Vfl I LU zes nne 3 aml 350 grades\ns Width The eIilltiFe Jiine\no iispiaYa T T are IB all sizes Take\nI ed will be cleaeect out e 0 A U G US 11 It U I your pJlcJk Hor e 0 e i J lJ 5\nJC\n1i lV 3JT4 J c t1iitJ7 Qo o\nt h l\n1 I 10 i ti Ja 7a i 4S4S 9a 7 Jt1f 2f enf\n1r\ncd\nL","height":"26391","width":"18939"}}
